dataIdInfo.idAbs: After authoring a classification dictionary, this tool allows the classification step. It is important to note that the BTM will not analyze your data for you and create a classification dictionary accordingly. The creation of a classification dictionary requires that the user have an understanding of their input data. There are several factors that need to be taken into consideration, such as the specific study area and the scale of the standardized BPI values (Weiss 2001). These factors will dictate the number and type of classifications that will be entered into the classification dictionary. The parameters that you enter to define these classifications are converted into a conditional statement that is evaluated to create the terrain classification data set during the final classification process.

tool.name: zoneclassification

param.name: Classification_dictionary
param.dialogReference: The classification dictionary specifies classes based on ranges of the input BPI rasters and slope. These are usually CSV or Excel Spreadsheets, but the tool can also import legacy XML dictionaries created with previous versions of the tool. See example dictionary for an example of one such classification. To author a dictionary, modify the provided sample in any spreadsheet program, and as long as the column order remains the same, the tool will find your classes.

param.name: Standardized_broad-scale_BPI_raster
param.dialogReference: A broad-scale BPI raster, after being normalized with the 'Standardize BPIs' tool.
param.pythonReference: A broad-scale BPI raster, after being normalized with the 'Standardize BPIs' tool.

param.name: Standardized_fine-scale_BPI_raster
param.dialogReference: A fine-scale BPI raster, after being normalized with the 'Standardize BPIs' tool.
param.pythonReference: A fine-scale BPI raster, after being normalized with the 'Standardize BPIs' tool.

param.name: Slope_raster
param.dialogReference: A slope raster, measuring the angle (in degrees) of the surface at that location.
param.pythonReference: A slope raster, measuring the angle (in degrees) of the surface at that location.

param.name: Bathymetry_raster
param.dialogReference: Input Bathymetric raster, can be of any type supported by ArcGIS. Expected values are negative elevation (depths) for bathymetric applications.
param.pythonReference: Input Bathymetric raster, can be of any type supported by ArcGIS. Expected values are negative elevation (depths) for bathymetric applications.

param.name: Output_zones_raster
param.dialogReference: The final output zones, a classified raster with classes corresponding to those provided in the classification dictionary.
param.pythonReference: The final output zones, a classified raster with classes corresponding to those provided in the classification dictionary.

tool.usage:
• When defining any parameter, it is OK to leave a parameter blank. The BTM Tool checks for empty parameters and uses this information to build the conditional statement.

  • When defining BPI parameters, use multiples of +/- 100 to define standard deviations around the mean (e.g. a value of 100 denotes 1 standard deviation from the mean). When defining optional slope and depth parameters, you can use the actual values.
